I saw an advertisement for outdoor wicker furniture with cushions with the setting being outside on a a patio along with a tea set on the matching table.  There was a man in sunglasses who appeared to give a positive statement about the company.

A boy in a red plaid shirt stands at the fore of the ad, above his head is text that reads something along the lines of, "It's my choice because it's the right choice." Behind him is a set of wicker patio furniture with plush cushions. Below the furniture, and to the left of the boy's torso is text describing the comfort of the furniture. /  / In my opinion, the furniture is playing second fiddle to the boy in the ad. The viewer's focus is on him, due to his placement at the forefront of the image and his bright red shirt. The furniture, meanwhile, plays a neutral background. If one didn't read the text of the image, they probably wouldn't realize it was an ad for patio furniture.
The female model wearing sunglasses though in agreement with the outdoor furniture set yet looking rather odd in the ad.  Seems like there's something to hide.

An ad for patio furniture, with a confident-looking man who has potentially picked out this furniture. I thought the text in the ad was awkward.
